\b \cf0 Pulse and ync
\b0 \
By default, plane uses open transport. This enables things like LFOs and encoder recording to stay in sync with the sequence. \
\
Sync options can be found under the pulse tab. Stat and stop the sequence with the large blue transport button. Tempo can be changed with the orange bpm setting. \
\
You can select 1/32 1/16 or 1/8 note pulses, as well as adjustable swing for fonky grooves.\
\
Two other pulse generators are provided, but you lose LFO and enc recorder sync. \
\
If you wish to drive plane from an analog sequencer, LFO, or other analog pulse source, take the audio output of your pulse generator and plug it into an input on your audio interface, then switch to 'analog' under the pulse tab. Select which audio input the pulse is plugged in to. You should see the level meter light up indicating received signal. Then set the pulse threshold to achieve consistent pulses. \
\
If you wish to sync plane to a MIDI beat clock source, the original stretta legacy sync (from polygome) is also provided. Set source to 'beat clock' and select which MIDI device is the beat clock source. Cool? Cool.\
\

\b Chord Scale
\b0 \
The current chord scale is shown under the chord scale tab in the top left hand corner of the window. This can be changed in real time. A MIDI controller can change the key value if desired. To do so, click on the MIDI tab, select a MIDI input device and set the menu to 'transpose'\
\
plane can follow a looping 'score' of changes if the 'score following' button is lit.   Each 'step' in a score is one 1/8th note. You can enter score changes using the score editor, but I find that once you understand the score format, it may be easier to edit the text file directly, or use a combination of the score editor and text editing to achieve the results you're looking for.\
\
