\b \cf0 Control voltages
\b0 \
Most of the control voltage outputs can be found under the outputs tab. There are three pitch outputs and two trigger outputs which will allow you to calibrate three oscillators. You could mult the trigger output in the analog realm, the additional trigger output is a convenience. \
\
To calibrate an oscillator, plug the sine wave output of your oscillator into an input on your audio interface and an output from your audio interface into the 1v/oct input on your oscillator. Both connections must be made.\
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural

\i \cf0 note: the pitch output must be enabled (the orange check box lit) before calibration can begin. If plane can't send control voltages, it can't calibrate.\
\
note: make sure you only enable appropriately routed outputs. If you enable an output that is used for audio, you can cause distortion or undesired/unpredictable results.
\i0 \
\
Make sure you've selected the proper output for the oscillator in the outputs tab. Go to the calibration tab and select the input from your oscillator. The level meter should light to indicate signal.\
\

\i note: make sure you know the proper output mappings of your audio interface. The numberings may not make sense. EG: analog 1 might be output 3. Also check your output mappings in the configure dsp menu,
\i0 \
\
Now you can calibrate. You should see a angled line appear of sample points. If you see a straight vertical line, something is wrong. \
\

\i note: Use shift-click to remove any rogue sample points. \
\
